            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>To the Editor of the Occident.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Sir.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I notice in your <date>December</date> No<lb/> that you charge the
                    <persName>Rev Solomon Jacobs</persName> with giving<lb/> “<hi rend="underline"
                    >paraphrase</hi>” which means to translate <hi rend="underline">freely</hi>, not
                    <hi rend="underline">literally</hi>, instead of “<hi rend="underline"
                    >translation</hi>”<lb/> which is directly opposed to “<hi rend="underline"
                    >paraphrase</hi>,” in the rendering of<lb/> Exodus 3. 14 <add>Hebrew</add>. In
                the Charity Sermon<lb/> which that Gentleman preached in this City, he gave the<lb/>
                following as the <hi rend="underline">True</hi> and <hi rend="underline"
                    >Literal</hi> version of this passage.</p>
            <p>“I will be unto them now that which I will be unto them hereafter.”</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">see |Published Sermon.|</p>
            <p>The <persName>Rev Mr Jacobs</persName> bears the reputation in this city of<lb/>
                being a profound Hebrew Scholar, therefore I think you<lb/> have been rather hasty
                in preferring a charge which<lb/> involves an ignorance of the Grammatical
                construction<lb/> of the Hebrew Language.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Truth, being the great “end” of all property conducted<lb/>
                <sic>controversey</sic>, you will best subserve that end by producing<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">authorities</hi> to support <del>your</del> the simple
                assertion<lb/> you have made in the premises,</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <persName role="author">an old Subscriber</persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <placeName>Charleston S.C.</placeName>
            </p>
            <p><date>December. 5613</date>.</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>My dear <addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">It is the general opinion of those who<lb/> prefer to be your
                friends, and mine also, that you<lb/> should give some elucidation to the position
                in which<lb/> you are pleased the better to enable you to do so I<lb/> have
                addressed the enclosed comment to the Ed of Occ,—<lb/> you can reply to this without
                noticing <persName>Mr. Is.</persName> letter at all<lb/> as this comn of mine may be
                dated <del>early</del> in <date>Dec.</date>, but too<lb/> late for Insertion for
                    <date>Jany.</date> Simply give the reply as<lb/> I wrote you last. All the
                authorities for translation under<lb/> that particular caption, and so with the
                paraphrases:<lb/> as many as possible, I have worded it so that your<lb/> reply must
                expose <hi rend="underline"><persName>Is.</persName> ignorance</hi>: which is as
                much<lb/> as you want to do all his assertions and personalities in the<lb/> bargain
                notwithstanding”</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The following vein of the subject you perhaps have not thought of.<lb/>
                <persName>Jacobs</persName>
                <hi rend="underline">preaches</hi> this sermon to a large audience, and makes<lb/>
                use of course of the same words—calling into question the <hi rend="underline"
                        >C<add>?</add></hi><lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">of the Nulgate</hi>, and giving <hi rend="underline">a true and
                    literal</hi> version his audience give him<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">credit</hi> for <hi rend="underline">great erudition</hi> and
                    <hi rend="underline">keenners of perception</hi> &amp;c &amp;c during the
                preaching<lb/> he <hi rend="underline">never mentions
                    “<persName>Rashi</persName>”</hi>. The audience think it his own,<lb/> he
                publishes it also without giving it as from “<persName>Rashi</persName>,” but as
                soon as the<lb/>
                <sic>plagarism</sic> is nailed on the head, lo and behold it is not<lb/> his, they
                are the <hi rend="underline">words of <persName>Rashi</persName></hi>, which <hi
                    rend="underline">are not <persName>Rashis</persName></hi>.<lb/> Why did he not
                tell the congregation so and not obtain from<lb/> them a surreptitious reputation
                for learning <del>which he to</del></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have copied <persName>Bernheims</persName> letter which is
                enclosed. I have<lb/> not been able to see this Sent yet. I most likely will<lb/>
                tomorrow.</p>
            <p>NB. If he had fancied or had known Aba<add>?</add> or<lb/> Saadial
                <add>?</add>pulation, and had adduced those instead<lb/> of
                    <persName>Rashi</persName>—of course a different mode of reasoning to<lb/> suit
                the several views would have been the result, but<lb/> I do firmly believe he never
                saw any other great sources of<lb/> information than <persName>Mendlesons</persName>
                Bible, with Targam, <persName>Beor</persName><lb/>
                <persName>Rashi</persName> and Medrach.—which are all he quotes, and<lb/> those not
                all correct.—vis <persName>Rashi</persName>.—&amp; Medrach,—</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have no time for more I am sleepy</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Yours Truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">
                    <hi rend="underline">Solomon</hi>
                </persName>
            </p>
            <p><date>Tuesday</date> night 11 ½ o ck</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <date>4<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Jun 1852</date>
            </p>
            <p>I wrote you the day before I got your last letter.</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Editor Occident</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>371 Walnut St</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
        </body>
